  "prompt": "How can I get a near-perfect SAT score by studying for 4 days?",
  "response": "Achieving a near-perfect SAT score in just 4 days is extremely challenging, but with focused, efficient, and strategic preparation, you can maximize your chances of performing well. Here\u2019s a step-by-step plan to optimize your study time:\n\n---\n\n### **Day 1: Understand the Test and Identify Weaknesses**\n1. **Familiarize Yourself with the SAT**  \n   - Review the test structure:  \n     - Evidence-Based Reading and Writing (Reading & Writing)  \n     - Math (divided into Calculator and No Calculator sections)  \n   - Understand the question types, time limits, and scoring system.\n\n2. **Take a Full-Length Practice Test**  \n   - Use an official SAT practice test from the College Board or Khan Academy.  \n   - Simulate test conditions (timed, no distractions).  \n   - This will help you identify your strengths and weaknesses.\n\n3. **Analyze Your Results**  \n   - Review every mistake and understand why you got it wrong.  \n   - Categorize errors by topic (e.g., geometry, grammar rules, reading comprehension).  \n\n---\n\n### **Day 2: Focus on High-Yield Strategies**\n1. **Reading and Writing**  \n   - **Reading:**  \n     - Practice skimming passages for main ideas and details.  \n     - Focus on evidence-based questions (find clues in the text).  \n   - **Writing:**  \n     - Review key grammar rules (subject-verb agreement, punctuation, sentence structure).  \n     - Practice improving sentence flow and clarity.  \n\n2. **Math**  \n   - **Concepts:** Focus on high-yield topics like algebra, linear equations, and data analysis.  \n   - **Calculator Use:** Use your calculator efficiently for complex calculations.  \n   - **Time Management:** Skip difficult questions and return to them later.  \n\n3. **Test-Taking Tips**  \n   - Learn to eliminate wrong answers.  \n   - Guess intelligently (SAT has no penalty for wrong answers).  \n\n---\n\n### **Day 3: Targeted Practice**\n1. **Practice Weak Areas**  \n   - Use Khan Academy or other resources to drill specific topics.  \n   - Focus on the categories where you lost the most points on the practice test.  \n\n2. **Timed Sections**  \n   - Practice individual sections under timed conditions to build speed and accuracy.  \n\n3. **Review Mistakes**  \n   - Keep a log of errors and revisit them to avoid repeating them.  \n\n---\n\n### **Day 4: Final Review and Simulated Test**\n1. **Take Another Full-Length Practice Test**  \n   - Simulate test conditions again to gauge progress.  \n\n2. **Review Strategies**  \n   - Revisit key concepts, formulas, and grammar rules.  \n   - Focus on confidence-building techniques (e.g., positive mindset, relaxation).  \n\n3. **Prepare for Test Day**  \n   - Gather materials (calculator, pencils, ID, admission ticket).  \n   - Get a good night\u2019s sleep and eat a healthy breakfast.  \n\n---\n\n### **Key Tips for Success**\n- **Be Realistic:** A near-perfect score is rare, even with extensive preparation. Aim for steady improvement.  \n- **Focus on Efficiency:** Use high-quality, official materials (College Board, Khan Academy).  \n- **Stay Calm:** Anxiety can hurt performance. Practice mindfulness or deep breathing techniques.  \n\nWhile 4 days is not ideal for SAT prep, this plan will help you make the most of your time. Good luck!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
